{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017934HfTBfwBhBBEhvdvnpz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ray-client pod is just sleeping. It's not running a Ray instance. So when we run `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` from within the client pod, it tries to connect to the remote Ray GCS.\n\nLooking at the error again more carefully:\n```\nCan't find a `node_ip_address.json` file from /tmp/ray/session_2026-06-23_14-13-51_055459_13\n```\n\nThe session was created at `14:13:51` - but the command was run at `14:13:55`. \n\nThe Ray session was created before our command even ran, which is strange since the client pod only runs `sleep infinity`. But when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is called, it initializes a Node object that tries to find the node IP address file in the session directory, and that's where it's failing.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that connecting to an external cluster with `ray.init(address=...)` starts a local Ray worker node on the current machine, not just a client connection. This local node needs system resources and a working temp directory to write its session files, but something's preventing that file from being created.\n\nThe ray-client pod is running a sleep process, and when I execute `ray.init` through kubectl, it spawns a new process that tries to initialize a Ray session. The session directory path includes the PID, but Ray likely can't start the local raylet process because the pod lacks sufficient shared memory—Kubernetes pods have very limited `/dev/shm` by default, which Ray's plasma store needs.\n\nI'm also noticing that the client is successfully connecting to the Ray cluster at `ray-head:6379`, but the problem occurs when it tries to start the local raylet worker node that should register with the head. This second step is failing, which is preventing the full initialization.\n\nThe raylet startup requires creating session directories in 