{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PL3Zue4yeSENEwc9iC97d9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ray head started successfully. The \"Ray runtime started\" message is there. The GCS is running at `10.244.0.18:6379`.\n\nNow the issue with the client: when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is called from the client pod, it:\n1. Resolves `ray-head` to `10.244.0.18` via DNS\n2. Connects to GCS at port 6379\n3. Tries to start a LOCAL Ray node on the client pod (a local worker)\n\nThe problem is that starting the local Ray node fails - specifically, the `node_ip_address.json` file isn't found. This file is written when the local raylet starts.\nI'm noticing the head pod is getting a warning about limited shared memory - it's falling back to `/tmp` instead of `/dev/shm` because there's only about 64MB available. This could be causing the raylet startup to fail on the client pod too, or there might be a separate issue preventing the local node from initializing properly.\n\nLooking at the stack trace, when `ray.init` is called with the external address, it's still trying to start a local raylet on the client pod. That raylet is timing out after 60 seconds while waiting for the node address file to appear, which suggests the raylet process itself isn't starting successfully.\n\nThe head node's connection instructions suggest using `_node_ip_address`, but that's not the right approach here. In Ray 2.x with KubeRay, the client should connect differently depending on whether it's in the same cluster or external.\n\nIf the client joins as a worker using the Ray client protocol on port 10001, it connects without needing its own raylet. But if it tries to start as a full worker node connecting to port 6379, it needs sufficient shared memory and the ability to spawn background processes like the raylet and plasma store—which is likely failing given the resource constraints. The head service only exposes port 6379, and the client pod isn't configured to run Ray processes, so option 2 is probably what's breaking. Let me check when this error actually occurred. The PID 13 created the session, and the timestamp aligns with when the command started at 14:13:55. Now I need to verify whether the ray-head service on port 6379 is actually reachable from the client pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2716,"cache_read_input_tokens":34043,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2716},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b0f7cce-530e-45a5-bbbc-8480d0191838","uuid":"86a0480f-b909-48f8-9631-b274d2adb5f9","request_id":"req_011CcLtGzMUdLxMLjzakj4BJ"}
